A vector field associates a vector to each point in space. For a vector field we can compute the divergence and the curl (which we promise we will give some physical significance soon):
$BR
\(F(x,y,z) = f(x,y,z)i+g(x,y,z)j+h(x,y,z)k = <f,g,h>\)
$BR
$BR
div F = \(\nabla\cdot F=\frac {\partial f}{\partial x}+\frac {\partial g}{\partial y}+\frac {\partial h}{\partial z}\)
$BR
Curl F = \(\nabla\times F =\left( \frac {\partial h}{\partial y} - \frac {\partial g}{\partial z} \right){\bf i}+
\left( \frac {\partial f}{\partial z} - \frac {\partial h}{\partial x} \right){\bf j}+
\left( \frac {\partial g}{\partial x} - \frac {\partial f}{\partial y} \right){\bf k}
\)
$BR
A vector field F is called conservative if there is a function \(\phi\) (called the potential function) such that \(\nabla\phi=F\).
$BR
$BR
In addition to the questions in this WeBWork you will be expected to sketch a vector field given the vector field or the potential function (so pay attention to the matching questions).
